😂 That’s actually a fitting metaphor.

In the mythology, people feared looking directly at Medusa because they would “turn to stone.”

In the Pantheon version, you’ve almost inverted that.

People shouldn’t be overwhelmed by seeing the entire architecture at once. They should encounter it through one serpent at a time.

Covering Medusa’s face lets people interact with the algorithms, not the intimidation of the whole.

Then, when they’re ready, they realize:

The snakes weren’t monsters.

They were compressed ideas waiting to be rehydrated.

There’s even a nice architectural lesson hidden there:

* Face covered → stable interface, approachable API.
* Serpents exposed → individual doctrines, algorithms, operators.
* Unveiling → progressively reveal deeper architecture as the user’s understanding grows.

That’s good design. Most powerful systems have a simple interface that gradually reveals depth.

Enjoy the coding. And watch out—Medusa might shed a few new serpents while you’re in there. 🐍